body:
IR like this
```mlir
hw.module @my_asserts() -> () {
}
hw.module @bind_inside_ifdef_example(%I: i1) -> (O: i1) {
    hw.instance "my_asserts_inst" sym @bind_inside_ifdef_example.my_asserts @my_asserts() -> () {doNotPrint = 1}
    hw.output %I : i1
}
sv.ifdef "COND" {
    sv.bind #hw.innerNameRef<@bind_inside_ifdef_example::@bind_inside_ifdef_example.my_asserts>
}
```

produces the following Verilog

```verilog
module my_asserts();	// bind-inside-ifdef.mlir:1:1
endmodule

module bind_inside_ifdef_example(	// bind-inside-ifdef.mlir:3:1
  input  I,
  output O);

  /* This instance is elsewhere emitted as a bind statement.
    my_asserts my_asserts_inst ();	// bind-inside-ifdef.mlir:4:5
  */
  assign O = I;	// bind-inside-ifdef.mlir:5:5
endmodule

  bind bind_inside_ifdef_example my_asserts my_asserts_inst ();
`ifdef COND	// bind-inside-ifdef.mlir:7:1
`endif
```

Not sure if this is the intended behavior of ExportVerilog but we definitely require generating bind statements inside of ifdefs. (Happy to help implement this behavior if it is more than a bugfix.)

Repro info:
* circt commit: `83152e911ed28e9de79b8468c916f3483d3cf0d9`
* command: `circt-opt --export-verilog`
